Column.name: Note
Column.value: Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorism Financing Act. Mandates that financial institutions implement customer due-diligence (CDD) and transaction monitoring programmes.

Column.name: Name
Column.value: LAW002 - GDPR and Data Protection Act

Column.name: Note
Column.value: General Data Protection Regulation. Governs the collection, storage, processing and transfer of personal data of EU/UK residents.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: EU Directive on Payment Services. Requires Strong Customer Authentication (SCA), open banking APIs, and liability rules for unauthorised payments.

Column.name: Name
Column.value: LAW004 - Basel III and CRR Capital Requirements

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Prudential capital adequacy framework requiring banks to hold sufficient capital against credit, market and operational risk.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: FCA Principle requiring firms to deliver good outcomes for retail customers across products, services, communications and support.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The bank must implement a risk-based KYC programme covering identity verification, beneficial ownership checks, PEP and sanctions screening for all new and existing customers.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The bank must monitor customer transactions in real-time to detect suspicious patterns and report Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs) to the National Crime Agency within 7 days.

Column.name: Name
Column.value: BR003 - Data Privacy and Consent Management

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The organisation must obtain, record and honour explicit customer consent for all data processing activities and support right-to-erasure requests within 30 days.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: All payment initiation and account access operations must enforce SCA using at least two independent factors (knowledge, possession, inherence) unless a defined PSD2 exemption applies.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The bank must expose PSD2-compliant Account Information and Payment Initiation APIs to authorised Third-Party Providers (TPPs) via a dedicated API gateway.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Finance must calculate and report CET1, Tier 1 and Total Capital ratios monthly and maintain buffers above regulatory minimum at all times.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Product owners must define, measure and evidence good consumer outcomes across the four FCA Consumer Duty outcomes on at least a quarterly basis.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The system must verify customer identity documents (passport, driving licence) using automated OCR and biometric liveness checks in real-time.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: For corporate customers the system must identify and record all beneficial owners holding 25% or more control via Companies House and LEI lookup.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The system must screen applicants against PEP lists and OFAC/UN/EU sanctions databases at onboarding and on every regulatory list update.

Column.name: Name
Column.value: NFR001 - Data Encryption at Rest and in Transit

Column.name: Note
Column.value: All customer PII and financial data must be encrypted using AES-256 at rest and TLS 1.3 in transit. Keys must be managed via a FIPS 140-2 Level 3 HSM.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The banking platform must undergo CREST-accredited penetration testing at least annually and after any major release.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: System access must be governed by RBAC. Privileged access must use just-in-time provisioning with full session recording.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: End-to-end payment authorisation must complete in less than 200 ms (p95) under peak load of 5,000 TPS.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The KYC service must support 1,000 concurrent onboarding sessions with identity verification completing in less than 10 seconds p99.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The system must calculate a composite KYC risk score (Low/Medium/High) based on geography, product type, transaction behaviour and PEP status, driving Enhanced Due Diligence (EDD) workflow for High-risk customers.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: High-risk customers must trigger an EDD workflow requiring relationship manager review, senior management approval and annual periodic review.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: All KYC decisions, evidence collected and approvals must be stored in an immutable audit log retained for a minimum of 5 years.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The payment system must screen every outbound and inbound transaction against configurable rule sets and ML-based anomaly models with a processing SLA of less than 50 ms p99.

Column.name: Name
Column.value: FR008 - Alert Generation and Case Management

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Alerts generated by transaction monitoring must be routed to an investigation queue. Analysts must be able to review, escalate or dismiss alerts with documented rationale.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The system must allow compliance officers to draft, approve and electronically submit SARs to the NCA ELMER system directly from the case management interface.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The payment gateway must enforce SCA before authorising any payment over the PSD2 low-value exemption threshold (EUR 30), integrating with the bank's biometric and OTP authenticators.

Column.name: Name
Column.value: FR011 - Open Banking Payment Initiation API

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The API platform must expose a PSD2-compliant /payments endpoint supporting domestic and SEPA credit transfers with OAuth 2.0 and FAPI security profile.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: The customer portal must present granular consent options for each processing purpose. Consent decisions must be timestamped and stored in the consent management platform.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Customer erasure requests submitted via the portal must trigger an automated workflow that anonymises personal data across all systems-of-record within 30 days, with a completion confirmation sent to the customer.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Customers must be able to submit DSARs online. The system must collate all personal data held and produce a structured report for the Data Protection team within 30 days.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Core banking and payment processing services must achieve 99.99% monthly availability (max 4.3 min downtime per month). RTO less than 30 min, RPO less than 5 min.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: A fully tested DR runbook must exist. DR failover must be rehearsed semi-annually with results reported to the Board Risk Committee.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: All compliance-relevant events (logins, approvals, SAR filings, consent changes) must be written to an immutable tamper-evident log retained for 7 years per FCA SYSC requirements.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: Capital adequacy, liquidity and transaction reports must be generated and submitted to the regulator within prescribed deadlines with zero tolerance for late filing.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: As a Compliance Analyst I want to review a customer KYC risk score and supporting evidence so that I can make an informed onboarding decision.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: As an MLRO I want to file a Suspicious Activity Report directly from the transaction alert so that I meet the 7-day statutory reporting deadline.

Column.name: Note
Column.value: As a Customer I want to view and update my data processing consents from the mobile app so that I can exercise my GDPR rights easily.

Column.name: Name
Column.value: US004 - Biometric Payment Auth User Story

Column.name: Note
Column.value: As a Customer I want to authenticate once using biometrics to initiate a payment so that I comply with SCA requirements without friction.

Column.value:
Requirements Management - FinTech / Banking
This model demonstrates how all requirements in a regulated financial institution are traced from primary legislation through business, functional and non-functional requirements down to user stories and system features.
Packages: Laws and Regulations - source legislation Business Requirements - obligations derived from law Functional Requirements - system capabilities to fulfil BR Non-Functional Requirements - quality attributes and constraints User Stories - agile stories linked to FR Stakeholders - actors who own or approve requirements

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
This diagram shows how each piece of primary legislation derives one or more Business Requirements using the 'derives' realisation connector (dashed arrow).
Status colour bar on each element: Green = Validated Yellow = Proposed Blue = Approved Grey = Implemented

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
KYC and Onboarding functional requirements are decomposed from BR001 using aggregation (diamond connector) to show the parent-child hierarchy.
Each requirement carries: Priority High / Medium / Low Status Validated / Approved / Proposed Author Requirements Team
Double-click any element to see its full property sheet.

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Payment and transaction monitoring requirements are derived from: BR002 - Transaction Monitoring (AML Act) BR004 - Strong Customer Authentication (PSD2) BR005 - Open Banking API Platform (PSD2)
The aggregation diamond shows parent-child decomposition. All High-priority requirements carry the blue Approved or green Validated status bar.

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Non-Functional Requirements are grouped into four quality domains.
Security - encryption, pen-test, RBAC Performance - latency, throughput Availability - uptime SLA, disaster recovery Regulatory Compliance - audit log, reporting SLA
NFRs are linked to Business Requirements via 'refine' dependency connectors to show which obligations drive each quality constraint.

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
End-to-end traceability for the AML / KYC requirement thread:
LAW001 (AML Act) derives --> BR001 (KYC Programme) aggregates --> FR001 Identity Verification --> FR003 PEP and Sanctions Screening --> FR004 Customer Risk Scoring trace --> US001 KYC Review User Story association --> Compliance Analyst
This diagram provides evidence of full requirements traceability as required by ISO/IEC 29148 and FCA SYSC 13 guidelines.

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
User Stories use the stereotyped Use Case pattern: 'As a [role] I want to [action] so that [benefit]'
Each User Story is: Linked to the relevant Functional Requirement via trace Associated to the accountable Stakeholder actor
Tagged values (Volatility, Priority) are shown in the element compartments when the Tags compartment is enabled on the diagram.
